 adopt a more nominalistic, skeptical way of thinking about American elections that highlights contingency, short-term election strategies, and valence issues. Or we might examine such broad topics as bellicosity in early American history, or racial questions in much of our electoral history. But we must move on from an old orthodoxy and failed model of illumination.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Apr 2020) 0aElectionsxHistoryxUnited States. 0aElectionszUnited StatesxHistory. 0aPartis politiquesxAdhésionxHistoirexÉtats-UnisxUnited States. 0aPartis politiquesxHistoirexÉtats-Unis. 0aParty affiliationxHistoryxUnited States. 0aParty affiliationzUnited StatesxHistory. 0aPolitical partiesxHistoryxUnited States. 0aPolitical partieszUnited StatesxHistory. 0aÉlectionsxHistoirexÉtats-Unis. 7aPOLITICAL SCIENCE / History & Theory.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertYUP eBook-Package 2000-2015z978311066772108iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertYale University Press eBook Package 2000-2013z978311053799440uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780300130034423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780300130034.jpg  a978-3-11-053799-4  Yale University Press eBook Package 2000-2013c2000d2013  a978-3-11-066772-1  YUP eBook-Package 2000-2015c2000d2015  aEBA_FAO  aGBV-deGruyter-alles